fp||cp|2|cs|3|ht|e|at|^b@2mitche: We all know that after 1NT opener, 2@d and 2@h are transfer bids to get the NT opener 
to be declarer.
But think about these problem hands: 

@sx, @hxxx,  @dQ109xxx, @cxxx and 
@Sx, @hAKx, @dAJ10xxx, @cKQx.

With the first hand, you want to play 3@d, and the second one might belong in 6 or 7 diamonds.
How can we deal with these 2 problems?  The answer is transfer bids, of course.

Here is the idea.  
We use 2@s as a transfer to 3@C and 
2NT as a transfer to 3@d.
The NT bidder doesn't know if responder has a good or terrible hand.  He will find out eventually.

Rule 1 of minor suit transfers - Notice that you have a bid in between the transfer bid and the transfer suit.  
After 2@S, opener can bid either 2NT or 3@c.
So when opener has good support for the transfer suit (after 2@S, that's @C) he uses the in-between bid (here, 2NT) to 
show 3-card support with an honor A,K,Q  (preaccepts); 
without good support (3 to a high honor), he just bids the transfer suit.  
(In between bids are 2NT over 2@S and 3@C over 2NT.)

So for example, the 1NT opener has @sKJ10x, @hAxxx, @dKQx, @cKx and hears 2@S. 
He bids 3@C because he does NOT have 3 to an honor.|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


nt||

cp|2|ht|c|3d|3|at|^b@2This is important, because when opener "preaccepts", responder can bid 3NT with 6 clubs to an honor,
hoping to run the suit.
Example:  Opener bids 1NT, responder has: 
@sQx, @hxx, @dKJ10xxx, @cJxx and bids 2NT over 1NT, transferring to @D.
If opener bids 3@c (the "preaccept bid"), responder might bid 3NT, hoping to produce 6 diamond tricks.
But responder can also sign off in 3 of a minor with a hopeless hand, something like:  @sx   @hxxx   @dQ109xxx   @cxxx

What happens when responder has hand 2, that monster:  @Sx   @hAKx   @dAJ10xxx   @cKQx?

He still bids 2NT over 1NT and whether or not opener bids 3@C or 3@D, responder bids 3@h. 
That says: "Game forcing, and I have a heart control."
Opener can now show a control  - 3@S, 4@c or even 4@d to show doubleton honor or 3 small.
(There are better uses for 4@d, but that would be way too much for tonite.)

Anyway, the idea is that responder either passes, bids a natural 3NT after the transfer to show a mildly slammish 
hand or a control bid to show a really good one.

Practice time:  

You have @sxx, @hAxx, @dKQJxx, @cxxx and partner bids 1NT - what do you do?|
