^b@2|at|If responder does have 4 spades after 2@c and opener bids 2@h, then responder should bid 2@S 
( information partner receives is: I was bidding the normal Stayman, asking for a Major) 
Opener bids 2@h with both majors (= up the line) => if responder has spades, he bids 2@S and if he doesn't, he bids 2NT.

The auction 1NT-2@C / 2@H-3NT denies a 4-card Major in responder's hand and shows GF points.
As long as opener bids 2@h with both majors, you cannot get it wrong.
When playing 4-way XFR, responder shows his 4-card @S suit by bidding them over 2@h.

masse24: With a GF hand, do you run the risk that opener can pass 2@S?
mitche:  If you want to play 3@S as GF, then you may.. but 2@S shows spades after 2@h and 2NT denies them.
I find it convenient to treat 2@S over 2@h as FORCING 1 ROUND so opener will raise to 3 with 4-4 in the majors 
or bid 2NT without 4 spades.

So what happened to invitational 2NT?  Remember that Stayman shows at least invitational values, so if you have a 4-4 
spade fit, you are safe at the 3 level with 15 HCP opposite 8+ or 9 HCP.
You use STAYMAN either with or without a 4-card Major.   If you have a 4-card Major, no problem, you bid as normal.
If you don't you just bid 2NT over opener's response. 
Let's summarize: After 1NT  2@c

Opener rebids 2@D
a) Responder bids 2NT with or without a major
b) Responder bids his 4-card Major, to show 5-4 in the Majors (2-level invite or 3-level GF Smolen
   or the variation: bid your 5-card at the 2-level, your 4-card at the 3-level.  Agree with P)
c) Responder bids 3NT: responder has 1 major

Opener rebids 2@h
a) responder bids 2@s with 4 spades
b) responder bids 2NT without a Major (invitational)
c) Responder bid 3NT which promises 4 spades|
