cp|2|ht|c|3d|3|at|^b@2Opener bids 2@s
a) Responder bids 2NT (may or may not have hearts) invitational
b) Responder bids 3NT which guarantees hearts
Reasoning: 
If, after Stayman 2@c, responder bids 3NT he must have a major, else he would bid 3NT directly over 1NT.

A further note: When the auction is 1NT - 2@c / 2@h (or 2@s) - 2NT, opener may still have a 5-card Major.
If opener rebids 3@h (or 3@s), it shows   "not minimum and 5-card suit"  
Responder should treat this as game-going and choose between 3NT or 4 of opener's Major.

ecolodge:  Question with 1NT-2NT:  How does opener know if this is a transfer to @D or just a weak, flat NT response?
mitche:  It is always a transfer to @D if you are playing 4-way transfers.  With weak flat hand, you pass 1NT.
With invitational flat hand, you go thru Stayman.  
And with strong flat hand, you bid 3NT or more (if you want to invite slam).

So the XFR allows you to sign off with a dog in 3 of a minor (6-card suit, probably fewer than 7 points).
NOTE:  If you have 7 or 8 points and a 6-card minor, I recommend passing because 1NT +1 
scores better than 3@C =
This is important for match point players.  That 8 point minor is something like Qxxxxx with an outside KQ or so. 

Example:  @sJxx   @hAx   @dxx   @cQ10xxxx     just passes 1NT and takes its chances .  
But  @sx   @hxx   @dxxx   @cQ10xxxxx          does not let opener struggle in 1NT and thus transfers to clubs.

